Featured Stories

Recession in Europe

Debosree Mukherjee

With Russia cutting off gas flows, many analysts are saying that a Europe-wide recession is inevitable. Record-high energy bills are coming for the winter, and even with substantial government support, Europe will be gripped with an affordability crisis.

Bloomberg Economics now has a 1% drop in GDP in their base case forecast for next year, and things could get worse than that with a cold winter. In that case, Bloomberg pegs the drop at as much as 5%. A drop this large would mirror the 2009 ‘great’ recession, an event almost nobody wants to repeat.

Oddly-enough, despite the coming energy crisis, solar panels are currently piling up in warehouses in Europe. Why? The installers are simply not available to complete installations fast enough.

Forever Energy - A New Way to Store Energy?

Yousaff Habib

The device you’re using to read this story likely uses a lithium battery. Lithium batteries have been the preferred option for short-term energy storage, but Forever Energy hopes to change this. As solar adoption has increased in the United States and Canada, energy storage has become more valuable. While some argue that lithium should be used for stationary battery technology, CEO of Forever Energy Craig Jones argues that vanadium flow batteries are a much more elegant solution. His company aims to make affordable vanadium flow batteries available for consumers to store their excess solar energy, as well as create options for commercial solar enterprises. Vanadium flow batteries are already seeing use in China, which is significantly further ahead than the rest of the world in the research, development and deployment of this battery type. Vanadium flow batteries offer many advantages over traditional lithium batteries — they are non-flammable and non-explosive, do not lose capacity over time, create less waste, last longer, and operate under a wider range of conditions

A Mockup of a Consumer Stationary Battery

Forever Energy is currently raising equity, and will see a final decision made by the Department of Energy for a $1.6 billion loan. Moreover, they are finalizing negotiations with the state of Louisiana to build the vanadium processing factory they require to create these batteries. Jones wants the US to have its own supply chain in vanadium processing, emphasizing that vanadium is a fairly common element, much more than lithium, and that nearly 99% of currently isolated vanadium is used in steel hardening. Steel production is mainly done in China, and Jones sees the need to divert vanadium supplies back to American soil. The US administration has also put manufacturing credits into place via the Inflation Reduction Act that Forever Energy can take advantage of. Overall, vanadium flow batteries are a definite contender in the stationary energy storage market, and with Forever Energy on the path of production, we are likely to see vanadium flow batteries sometime soon. For more information, check out this article as well as Forever Energy’s website.

(Less than) Green Energy?

Marc Vermette

Drax, a company that has received £6bn GBP ($9.2bn CAD) in renewable energy subsidies from UK taxpayers, is cutting down important forests in Canada.

The company runs the UK’s largest power station. It burns millions of tonnes of imported wood pellets, which is considered to be a form of renewable energy.

The BBC has discovered some of these wood pellets come from primary forests in Canada, despite the company’s claims that it only uses sawdust and waste wood.

Satellite images show forests cut down in British Columbia. Image credits to Planet Labs PBC.

Through the analysis of satellite images, logging licenses, drone footage, and truck routes, reporter Joe Crowley verified that Drax was logging entire trees from forests that have taken thousands of years to grow.

“It’s really a shame that British taxpayers are funding this destruction with their money. Logging natural forests and converting them into pellets to be burned for electricity, that is absolutely insane,” Ecologist Michelle Connolly said.

The Drax power station in Yorkshire is an ex-coal-burning plant, which produces 12% of the UK’s renewable energy, despite wood burning’s controversial status as a renewable energy source among environmentalists.
